That is the place where Pantheon becomes more than “prompt style.” It becomes a governed agent pipeline.

What Claude Code specifically teaches Pantheon

First, externalized behavior wins. The important stuff is not buried in the weights; it is moved into editable files, extensions, and policies. Claude’s docs make that plain through CLAUDE.md, skills, settings, and extension layers.  ￼

Second, permissions are architecture, not an afterthought. Anthropic’s sandboxing and auto-mode work shows that constrained autonomy is the practical path: more agency inside declared boundaries, not less agency overall.  ￼

Third, agent quality depends on scaffolding. Official best-practices and product docs emphasize environment setup, parallel sessions, project configuration, and tool-connected workflows, which supports your long-running thesis that the useful unit is not just the model but the orchestrated system around it.  ￼

